data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code. Here's each one and the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — no longer accepts expression trees

The setter parameter changed from `Expression<Func<...>>` to `Func<...>`. Your manual expression tree code **won't compile**.

**Fix** — replace the entire block with a simple lambda:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda`, `Expression.Call`, etc. Conditionals go directly inside the lambda body.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — now auto-uniquified & nested paths changed

Two related changes:

- **Uniquification**: `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously silently shared one `Street` column. EF 10 appends a number (e.g. `Street`, `Street1`) to avoid data corruption.
- **Nested full path**: `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` previously mapped to `BillingAddress_City`. Now it maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City`.

**Fix** — if you have an existing database and need to preserve column names, pin them explicitly:

```csharp
// Same-name properties across complex types:
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});

// Nested complex types — preserve old (short) column name:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

If you're creating a fresh database, the new defaults are fine — no action needed.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter for redacted SQL logging.

**Fix** — add the parameter to each method:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (sensitive data redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual execution SQL
    }
}
```

Apply the same addition to `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, `CommandScalarExecuted`, `CommandNonQueryExecuting`, `CommandNonQueryExecuted`, and any other methods you implement from the interface.
